nit: shellcheck wiki suggests `# shellcheck source=/dev/null` instead

https://www.shellcheck.net/wiki/SC1090
Done
oh. I guess this is a bug then. I wonder if this has cause any issue in our system before.
Done

Can you move this to after the copyright header?

Should make it easier to see, and I think Google prefers the copyright to go directly after the shebang
I thought it was required to go right after the shebang, but it looks like moving it lower after the copyright is also passing shellcheck.
Thanks! Can you make this change to the other files under gbmc-bridge too?
Fixed any I found in the 2nd line of any script in the meta-layer.
We should remove all of the exports added in this change. These variable are not intended to be used by subprocesses or outside the shell environment.

I'm not sure what you'd like me to do here.  Shellcheck warns about these variables being written to without use.  They are used by scripts that are sourcing them.  Is there really any harm in the export?  Is there some other way of you know of to inform of the use outside the calling function, besides export?

Why does it want to put everything inside an if... It's weird that we end up having to indent everything below an extra level.

Can we invert the check and return somehow?

Shellcheck can't seem to figure out this whole "this file can be sourced and called directly" pattern.  This seemed to be the recommendation.  Let me see if the logic can be inverted but without this I got a lot of "the code after this point can never be executed" warnings.

Looks like it can be inverted so I'll give that a try.
Can we keep the name to reflect other naming?

No, because it conflicts with the name used elsewhere.  In other places the name 'bytes' is used as an array and shellcheck (rightly) warns of this as a redefinition.


```
 │     Variable was used as an array but is now assigned a string. shellcheck (2178) [160, 12]
```
fix indent
Done
over two weeks have elapsed with no actionable feedback. please address this.
Should I merge this as-is?  I've seen other changes being merged in meta-google but I've gotten no additional feedback in almost a month.
Sorry, my plan was to upload some proposed tweaks to this.

I'm slightly annoyed at how long this is taking.  It's been almost 2 months now and the meta-google scripts keep getting in worse and worse shape.  There already more shellcheck errors that need to be fixed.

I'm going to do the following:

- rebase this commit onto the one you put up the other day that removes the source/exec protection.
- split the scripts you gave comments on out into another commit
- fix up the latest issues in scripts that have regressed.

I'd like to see this commit merged rather quickly next week or else let me know which further scripts you would like to see split out.  This is work that Google should have already been doing over the last 2 years and I shouldn't have to keep investing more and more time into it myself.
